When I originally found this bird, I was struck by the very pale orange throat and buffy forehead. I have seen Cave Swallow before, but not recently, so I reached out to a few people and eventually a group accumulated to view the bird. We were treated to some pretty incredible views as it repeatedly circled in front of the stretch of shore we had occupied. We continued to discuss the ID and compare photos for a couple hours, before moving on, ultimately puzzled. After photos were reviewed, and we have made ourselves more aware of all the subtle intricacies that separate these two species (Cliff and Cave), Ethan Monk concluded that the brown back and white rump likely indicate retained juvenile plumage, effectively accounting for the lighter throat and overall odd appearance. Could not have said it better myself. Fun bird!

When I originally found this bird, I was struck by the very pale orange throat and buffy forehead. I have seen Cave Swallow before, but not recently, so I reached out to a few people and eventually a group accumulated to view the bird. We were treated to some pretty incredible views as it repeatedly circled in front of the stretch of shore we had occupied. We continued to discuss the ID and compare photos for a couple hours, before moving on, ultimately puzzled. After photos were reviewed, and we have made ourselves more aware of all the subtle intricacies that separate these two species (Cliff and Cave), Ethan Monk concluded that the brown back and white rump likely indicate retained juvenile plumage, effectively accounting for the lighter throat and overall odd appearance. Could not have said it better myself. Fun bird!

Pas encore de jeunes visibles. Face sud : Aucune activité lors de notre visite. La quantité de boue posée sous le toit ne semble pas avoir augmenté. Site 3 (maison jaune) - Face ouest : Au moins 5 nids encore actifs. 4 jeunes visibles. Face est : Aucune activité notée et pas de jeunes visibles.  Site 4 (garage jaune) - Face sud : 2 nids artificiels occupés, 2 jeunes visibles. Nid naturel toujours actif. Site 5 (structure de nidification) : Une quinzaine d’HIFB, tournent autour de la structure. Nid 5E1 - un adulte à l’intérieur. Nid 5E2 - 2 jeunes à l'intérieur se font nourrir. Nid 5E3 - un adulte à l’intérieur. Du côté ouest, les 5 nids (5O1 à 5O5) sont visités par des jeunes et des adultes.  Beaucoup d’hirondelles sur le site aujourd’hui avec une majorité d’Hirondelles de rivage qui se posent souvent au sommet des conifères dans la cour de la maison jaune en compagnie de quelques Hirondelles à front blanc et bicolores. Les hirondelles nichent  à 4 endroits  sur l'île Charron. Elles utilisent l'intérieur d'une grosse barge de métal ancrée (abandonnée) dans la baie à l'est du pont-tunnel. À noter que la barge ne figure pas sur la photo de Google Earth, qui date de 2013. Les coordonnées figurent sur la photo jointe. Cela fait 4 ans que cette barge gît à cet endroit et les hirondelles en profitent chaque année. On ne peut y voir le nombre de nids, mais il y a quelques dizaines d'hirondelles qui la fréquente. D'autres individus construisent leurs nids sur les parois des deux grandes tours de ventilation du pont-tunnel depuis plusieurs années. Quelques nids ont aussi été vus près du sommet du grand radar blanc chaque année, mais cette année, des travaux sur cette structure les empêchent de procéder. Le quatrième endroit est sous le pont du pont-tunnel, soit entre l'île charron et la rive sud. L'inaccessibilité des lieux nous empêche d'y dénombrer les nids, mais la colonie ne semble pas très populeuse.

Four house martin sized swallows with pointed, short, triangular but broad wings, a small head, and a very distinguishable squared tail were seen over the SW cliffs of Heimaey island in Vestmannaeyjar archipelago. The swallows looked darkish brown with deep chestnut coloured throats, rich, brick-red/rusty coloured cheeks and sides of neck, dark blue/black lower throat or some mixing of black, white, grey or cinnamon; and dark cap extending below eye. They also showed whitish underparts including flanks, whitish underwings, which contrasted with their dark head and throat. They had visible pale or light cream/rusty foreheads. The rumps were of a clear cinnamon/pale orange or pale buff colour. The crown and back were between visibly glossy dark blue and dark but lacking iridescent hue. All four brds were watched for approx. 2 hours gliding fearlessly near the cliffs, often in a very close proximity to the observers (sometimes 2-3m close!).

Observation Details: I found this nest yesterday while playing in the creek with my girls. It appeared to be built this year and has a large pile of bird droppings underneath the entrance hole.  I came back this morning to take a picture of the nest so I could be sure if it was a cliff swallow nest as it is a solitary nest, and I thought they only nested in colonies. When I got under the bridge, a cliff swallow popped his head out and then flew off.  I sat where I could watch the nest for a few minutes and saw 2 birds visit and enter the nest multiple times. There was possibly a 3rd bird flying with them when they were soaring the air above the bridge, but I'm not 100% sure, so I'm only reporting 2.

Found a number of CLSW colonies this morning while traversing the east side of the square. At the first location I had a number of adults entering and exiting nests under a concrete culvert. There were only 4 nests so this was a small colony. At the 2nd site I had another small group under the concrete culvert at the next intersection up. Next up was a much larger colony with FY sitting on the hydro lines just near the large concrete culvert and begging food from the adults who were flying around. Estimated 40 birds at this colony and photographed some of them sitting on the wires. There was also a large pond right by the road here. At the last site of the morning I only had 3 adults flying around near a large concrete culvert but I didn't take time to check for nests as the thunderstorms were almost on top of me.

Media notes: I went to the CJ Strike dam campground looking for White Pelicans. When I got there I observed swarms of Cliff Swallows gathering mud for nests.  I parked nearby and used my vehicle for a photo blind. It was like trying to photograph chaos. The birds swarmed, both in flight and on the ground. It was the first time I observed this behavior and I was struck by what appeared to be physical combat between some birds. When I got home, research indicated that what I was observing was Extra-Pair Copulations. Here are 10 images of different EPC events among (I believe) different birds. If you would like more of the mud gathering activity, please let me know.

Observation Details: When I originally found this bird, I was struck by the very pale orange throat and buffy forehead. I have seen Cave Swallow before, but not recently, so I reached out to a few people and eventually a group accumulated to view the bird. We were treated to some pretty incredible views as it repeatedly circled in front of the stretch of shore we had occupied. We continued to discuss the ID and compare photos for a couple hours, before moving on, ultimately puzzled. After photos were reviewed, and we have made ourselves more aware of all the subtle intricacies that separate these two species (Cliff and Cave), Ethan Monk concluded that the brown back and white rump likely indicate retained juvenile plumage, effectively accounting for the lighter throat and overall odd appearance. Could not have said it better myself. Fun bird!

Locality: Ten Mile Estuary State Marine Reserve

Observation Details: *High count. This was the most common swallow in a flock of 150-200 swallows and swifts. The first swallows I got on were a small group of Cliffs, and then I realized that about half of the swallows were Cliffs. The buff rumps, white foreheads, and dark red throats set these apart from the others. I scanned through the flock attempting counts multiple times, and always got 50-60 birds each time. These birds were whirling around each other, so this is my best minimum estimate. As well, I estimated the flock size, and estimated that Cliffs were nearly half of the swallows, which concurred with my count estimate of 50-60 birds. A few times the flock condensed, allowing for some photos with 6-10 birds. Around 8:30 am, about half the birds got quite high and dispersed in all different directions. Interestingly, the Middlesex County high count is 50 birds on this same date in 2003 at this location by Simon Perkins.

Four house martin sized swallows with pointed, short, triangular but broad wings, a small head, and a very distinguishable squared tail were seen over the SW cliffs of Heimaey island in Vestmannaeyjar archipelago. The swallows looked darkish brown with deep chestnut coloured throats, rich, brick-red/rusty coloured cheeks and sides of neck, dark blue/black lower throat or some mixing of black, white, grey or cinnamon; and dark cap extending below eye. They also showed whitish underparts including flanks, whitish underwings, which contrasted with their dark head and throat. They had visible pale or light cream/rusty foreheads. The rumps were of a clear cinnamon/pale orange or pale buff colour. The crown and back were between visibly glossy dark blue and dark but lacking iridescent hue. All four brds were watched for approx. 2 hours gliding fearlessly near the cliffs, often in a very close proximity to the observers (sometimes 2-3m close!).

Locality: Jackson Park, Chicago--Wooded Island/Bobolink Meadow area

Observation Details: Found a number of CLSW colonies this morning while traversing the east side of the square. At the first location I had a number of adults entering and exiting nests under a concrete culvert. There were only 4 nests so this was a small colony. At the 2nd site I had another small group under the concrete culvert at the next intersection up. Next up was a much larger colony with FY sitting on the hydro lines just near the large concrete culvert and begging food from the adults who were flying around. Estimated 40 birds at this colony and photographed some of them sitting on the wires. There was also a large pond right by the road here. At the last site of the morning I only had 3 adults flying around near a large concrete culvert but I didn't take time to check for nests as the thunderstorms were almost on top of me.

Observation Details: When I originally found this bird, I was struck by the very pale orange throat and buffy forehead. I have seen Cave Swallow before, but not recently, so I reached out to a few people and eventually a group accumulated to view the bird. We were treated to some pretty incredible views as it repeatedly circled in front of the stretch of shore we had occupied. We continued to discuss the ID and compare photos for a couple hours, before moving on, ultimately puzzled. After photos were reviewed, and we have made ourselves more aware of all the subtle intricacies that separate these two species (Cliff and Cave), Ethan Monk concluded that the brown back and white rump likely indicate retained juvenile plumage, effectively accounting for the lighter throat and overall odd appearance. Could not have said it better myself. Fun bird!

Observation Details: ***edit; most likely an abnormal Cliff, but documentation of rump & DNA need.   First detected by Mason Jarrett earlier in the day. Clearly not a typical Cliff Swallow by dark forecrown, nearly matching throat with dark brick red color. Hybrid is a consideration given the presence of 2 Cave Swallows at mixed nests with Cliff Swallows here in spring/summer 2016; however, melanogaster Cliff Swallow should still be considered. Examples of Cave X Cliff hybrid are scarce (ex: S36717443 & S45364159; 2 records in eBird from the same locality in FL, likely the same individual), so no knowledge of how much appearance of this hybrid can vary due to its rarity. Was unable to obtain rump photos since entrance/exit from nest was very quick and only happened twice during my time there. However, Mason Jarrett reported seeing the rump well and described it as darker than that of a standard Cliff, more like “burgundy red.” Rump photos, and potentially DNA may be needed to confirm ID definitively.

I carefully estimated there to be 1800 near the chlorine-contact basin, 500 on the storage-pond bank, 300 each on the two bridge structures at the southeast corner of facultative pond #3 and the north side of the storage afterbay, 200 on the bridge structure between the irrigation forebay and the outflow channel, and 150 on the bridge structure between the north recirculation channel and the storage forebay. Many additional birds were seen in flight over all ponds and in small concentrations resting on various structures around the ponds complex.

Locality: Dufferin Aggregates Milton Quarry - North Quarry
Observation Details: First day Cliff Swallows appeared at the quarry this year, a week later than usual. While it's too soon to tell at this early date (and I have yet to return to the North Quarry to check as of the date of posting this report - May 21) the relatively small number of birds, even for the advance guard is disturbing. Cliff Swallows have been using the vertical rock faces in the quarry for the 10 years I've worked there and in huge numbers. When this particular habitat (which faces west) was created the birds quickly formed their largest colony to date. 2 years ago there was 160-180 nests on this face. Last year there was 16 and the numbers of Cliff Swallows across the quarry was considerably smaller than previous years. As conditions at the quarry remain optimum (as in good nesting habitat and many marsh and quiet water areas for habitat of their flying insect prey) and unchanged, in fact there is even more of it, one can only assume the alarming shrinkage in numbers is attributable to something occurring during their migratory journeys or where they spend their winter months. Even taking this colony and other North Quarry birds from the equation there is a disturbing down-trend in their numbers in other parts of the quarry. In just a couple of years Cliff Swallows have gone from multiple birds being seen numerous times on a daily basis in the main quarry to a rare occurrence of 1 and sometimes 2 individuals.

Cliff Swallows have been using the vertical rock faces in the quarry for the 10 years I've worked there and in huge numbers. When this particular habitat (which faces west) was created the birds quickly formed their largest colony to date. 2 years ago there was 160-180 nests on this face. Last year there was 16 and the numbers of Cliff Swallows across the quarry was considerably smaller than previous years. As conditions at the quarry remain optimum (as in good nesting habitat and many marsh and quiet water areas for habitat of their flying insect prey) and unchanged, in fact there is even more of it, one can only assume the alarming shrinkage in numbers is attributable to something occurring during their migratory journeys or where they spend their winter months. Even taking this colony and other North Quarry birds from the equation there is a disturbing down-trend in their numbers in other parts of the quarry. In just a couple of years Cliff Swallows have gone from multiple birds being seen numerous times on a daily basis in the main quarry to a rare occurrence of 1 and sometimes 2 individuals.

Four house martin sized swallows with pointed, short, triangular but broad wings, a small head, and a very distinguishable squared tail were seen over the SW cliffs of Heimaey island in Vestmannaeyjar archipelago. The swallows looked darkish brown with deep chestnut coloured throats, rich, brick-red/rusty coloured cheeks and sides of neck, dark blue/black lower throat or some mixing of black, white, grey or cinnamon; and dark cap extending below eye. They also showed whitish underparts including flanks, whitish underwings, which contrasted with their dark head and throat. They had visible pale or light cream/rusty foreheads. The rumps were of a clear cinnamon/pale orange or pale buff colour. The crown and back were between visibly glossy dark blue and dark but lacking iridescent hue. All four brds were watched for approx. 2 hours gliding fearlessly near the cliffs, often in a very close proximity to the observers (sometimes 2-3m close!).

Next up was a much larger colony with FY sitting on the hydro lines just near the large concrete culvert and begging food from the adults who were flying around. Estimated 40 birds at this colony and photographed some of them sitting on the wires. There was also a large pond right by the road here. At the last site of the morning I only had 3 adults flying around near a large concrete culvert but I didn't take time to check for nests as the thunderstorms were almost on top of me.

Observation Details: When I originally found this bird, I was struck by the very pale orange throat and buffy forehead. I have seen Cave Swallow before, but not recently, so I reached out to a few people and eventually a group accumulated to view the bird. We were treated to some pretty incredible views as it repeatedly circled in front of the stretch of shore we had occupied. We continued to discuss the ID and compare photos for a couple hours, before moving on, ultimately puzzled. After photos were reviewed, and we have made ourselves more aware of all the subtle intricacies that separate these two species (Cliff and Cave), Ethan Monk concluded that the brown back and white rump likely indicate retained juvenile plumage, effectively accounting for the lighter throat and overall odd appearance. Could not have said it better myself. Fun bird!

Basically, standing between the water and the columns on the east side of the water. I saw two chicks in the nest and an adult came and fed them on three occasions, 10 to 15 minutes apart. It could be more than one adult doing the feeding but I didn't see two at the same time. The two photos of the adult are a computer screenshot of a video I took of the feeding process that takes a fraction of a second only each time.

Observation Details: An unseasonal flock of 8 Cliff Swallows plus two Tree Swallows was present from noon to 13:30 at least today. Feeding over Renews harbour, often coming close to highway, also occasionally very high in the sky. No Caves! Newfoundland gets the occasional August sighting of Cliff Swallow but the best season for Cliffs-by-the-flock is mid Sept to late October. A southern wind began around noon.  Spent 3.5 hours in the alders from Renews to Cappahayden this morning taking an early stab at Southern Warblers. none found. Resident species were present in abundance.  Rough Totals  Yellow Warbler - 30 Northern Waterthrush - 25 Black-and-white Warbler - 25 Wilson's Warbler - 20 Blackpoll Warbler - 18 Yellow-rumped Warbler - 15 Common Yellowthroat - 12 American Redstart - 1 Mourning Warbler - 1  Yellow-bellied Flycatcher - 15 Gray-cheeked Thrush - 1 superb view, adult. one minute, couldn't reach for camera cause it was too close to make a movement. Best look in years. Hermit Thrush - 6  B Mactavish

Media notes: Gathering mud for nests.
Observation Details: At the farm at the corner of Crane and Fry Roads.  We haven't had rain in several weeks, so with the rain that fell overnight, the mud puddle these birds were using to make their nests was again muddy.  These birds seem to be nest-building very late in the season.  Perhaps their first nests were knocked down by humans, or taken over by House Sparrows.  This farm was loaded with House Sparrows.  Barn Swallows were also gathering mud at this location and entering the barn.  The Cliff Swallows would fly into the main, large door on the north side of the barn with their loads of mud in their beaks.

Cliff Swallow | HausSparrow.com
Observation Details: Arrived at the Theodore Roosevelt footbridge, leading to the island, via kayak at about 9 a.m. and proceeded to paddle the length of the bridge to count the activity of the Cliff Swallows. I observed this location for about 45 minutes.   I started my observations from the point where the bridge connects to the island and then went towards the end that meets the main parking lot. The bridge has very "segmented" sections and I used this to do the following breakdown (the nests varied from being completely "jug"-like to very partially built):  Segment 1 = 7 nests in varying stages. In this section I could safely count 4 Cliff Swallows either occupying the nest or bringing in materials to add to a nest. The rest of the details will follow this similar pattern. Segment 2= 8 nests/ 6 Cliff Swallows Segment 3= 10 nests/ 2 Cliff Swallows Segment 4= 5 nests/ 5 Cliff Swallows Segment 5= 6 nests/6 Cliff Swallows Segment 6= 7 nests/6 Cliff Swallows Segment 7= 4 nests/2 Cliff Swallows Segment 8= 4 nests/3 Cliff Swallows Segment 9= 5 nests/2 Cliff Swallows Segment 10= 8 nests/ 2 Cliff Swallows Segment 11= 9 nests/ 0 Cliff Swallows Segment 12= 3 nests/ 0 Cliff Swallows  This high total number is accurate to what I observed as a lot of the Cliff Swallows I observed were individually occupying a nest and were not leaving them at the time. Other nest builders would fly in with regular consistency into their "assigned" segment and I could view some of this activity as I moved onto another segment and looked back and points that I had already passed.   Other notes: At this time, the more "complete" jug nests seemed to be in the corners on the side that crosses the span of the river and is on the parking lot side ("north"). This is pretty similar to what I observed last year.   One content Cliff Swallow that was occupying a complete jug nest was observed to leave the nest to fly a couple of feet to another nest that was only about 1/4 done — to snag fresh mud from 2 Cliff Swallows that were on their nest and building it up. It was basically a "landing platform" and they seemed to be doing their best to fend off the greedy invader.  There was a photographer above on the middle of the bridge doing a photoshoot of some people and the bridge was being heavily trafficked by visitors to the island. So when I first arrived there did not appear to be much aerial activity from the Cliff Swallows. After a bit they started to leave the bridge and proceed to the bank to get mud for their nests and became more active. Conditions were warming up and the sun was out.

Observation Details: I thought this was an excellent candidate for a Cave Swallow initially but review by others were not conclusive. With a yard list over 210 species, I’ve had surprisingly few Cliffs here in 20 years - only two previous  records - so I had interest in photographing this bird. As I did, I began to notice the very pale throat and nape all the same straw color, which got me wondering if this wasn’t a young Cave. Dark cap, drab brown upperparts, white underparts, squared off tail, pale rump. Appears to be a juvenile.

Observation Details: Sitting in the road on the edge of death JRR: interesting phenomenon I have never witnessed before; highway littered with dead and dying swallows of several species (CLSW, BARS, TRES, and NRWS).  I am thinking it is trans-Gulf migrants that arrived overnight/that morning, only to find no insects to forage upon due to low temperatures brought in by cold front (about 42F on this day). It is a sight to see all those fresh made mud nests shaped like gourds or jugs.  The activity of the birds coming and going is hard to describe however not quite "frantic".  But almost.  From looking up over head the bird displays a square tail, a dark throat patch and a rusty or what might be called a "Buffy" rump area. In the air the species displays a long elliptical glide with a very steep pitched climb. Around the colony area vocals are a low "chur" or alarm note "keer" other notes being somewhat guttural sounding gratings.  Photos are by Friend "Randy".  And are there as documentary.

Small and stocky swallow with mostly squared off tail. Dark throat with a clean cut-off to clean undersides. Initially dismissed as a TRES in lieu of the double BWHA show, I am thinking otherwise now. TOY is getting late for TREW, and with the tail shape and dark throat, I am pushed away from TRES. These features also pushed me away from NRWS. PUMA I feel would be larger overall, longer body and winged, and a larger tail. Maybe a bit dirtier undersides as well. I asked a local veteran what his thoughts were and they agreed CLSW was the likely ID! Glad I took a few pot shots! FOS!

Awesome to witness a cliff swallow migration streaming directly southward at a rate of 30-50 per minute, mostly over Mosquito Lagoon. Continuing for two hours while we were there, with lower rates towards the end of our visit. A few bank, rough-winged, and barn swallows were sprinkled in, but cliff swallows were the vast majority. Most of the barn swallows were over the dunes at the beach or even over the ocean. Multiplying the low rate by two hours would make a low estimate of 3600. Some photos attached.

Second time was a charm. Location: 42.24552° N, 71.13644° W Fantastic find of apparently breeding Cliff Swallows for Suffolk County and Boston. Smallish swallow with dark metallic blue back and upper side of wing coverts. Primaries brownish. Wings less sharply pointed than say BARS. Back had two rows of light streaking. Dark mask. Throat and nape were dark maroon. Forehead a gleaming white “headlight”. Light collar on back of neck. Rump pale tawny/light orange. Could not hear them if they were calling due to traffic noise. For me, no more than two were in view simultaneously, though others have said more may be involved. They stayed almost exclusively on west side of River Street Bridge over Mother Brook. They made infrequent sallies to the underside of the bridge; basically where the bridge overhangs, but not under the bridge itself. Basically right under where one can stand when on the bridge. I could not see the actual nest(s); it was unclear if they were feeding young or still constructing nest(s). I suspect feeding young as I observed them actively hunting insects, and none of my photos show daubs of mud in their bills. I found the best spot to observe the birds was from the river bank on the north side. This also gets you away from the traffic and noise. Cross the bridge going north on River Street and turn left (west) on Fairview Avenue. Almost immediately there will be a little path to the bank which provides a clear view of the bridge and the “nesting site”.

Observed at a nest colony of swallows located under a bridge spanning the Rappahannock river. I have several low quality cell phone pictures, but I will attach them regardless, as soon as I get the chance. Individuals had dark blue back and wings and an off white underside. I distinctly remember seeing an orange rump, though that does not seem to come through in any of the pictures I took. Individuals lacked the prominent forked tail of a barn swallow. I had observed this colony earlier in the year, but this time their numbers were far greater. I did not have binoculars, and individuals were moving quite often, making an accurate count difficult, but I attempted a rough estimate counting by fives. Likely an underestimate.
